gostaria convidar seguinte carol auditório i dimapufrn afeira participação evento contabilizada atividade dim seminários cc agradecemos participação ampla divulgação horário título computability theory and uncomputable numbers palestrante débora tayná bti ufrn resumo the theory putability greatly developed from the first half of the twentieth ought with it some forms rigorous enough to classify which functions would be putable at the time several models putation were proposed and later on the equivalence between them was proven when it was realized that it was possible to simulate one model within another the talk will present an overview of two of these models developed to capture in formal way the intuitive concept putability turing machines and partial recursive functions after introducing these concepts we will deal more directly with putable real numbers with the objective of knowing some of their different definitions and some properties of the set formed by these numbers in addition to the computable reals another very important concept in the theory of computability will be explored the concept of putable entities the halting problem and some of the known putable numbers will be investigated horário título the last wont be the first fuzzy games and the winning strategy impartial games palestrante joão mendes bcc ufrn resumo combinatorial game theory is anch of game theory concerned with usually two players games in which randomization plete information about them are provided to their players in this theory there is way to attribute numbers to games but once we add impartiality there can be games namely fuzzy that can not be associated neither to positive nor negative numbers nor to such games share the particularity that the first player can always win by playing intelligently in this seminar we are going to explore these fuzzy games focusing on an binatorial impartial game called nim well how the first player winning strategy it can be generalized to other impartial games

martin st summit school on data science based geophysics connections challenges research opportunities in the context of the cnrs edi france brazil adageo november th december rd online website registration let us dig into the geophysics of data objective the adageo summit and thematic school aim at promoting scientific discussion and practical actions and projects that can address geosciences problems through data science solutions thereby the activities and interaction in this event will build scientific and practitioners munity the will develop novel way of doing geosciences overview massive data production is critical aspect of experimental sciences we have experienced exponential growth in data availability in the past decade and it has not been different geoscience examples of geoscientific data include any physical observable related to the energy industry mining monitoring hazardous areas eg effects of mining in populated areas etc nowadays with the relative facility and lowering the cost to acquire data even in continuous mode the data processing to exploit their value is challenge also it requires expertise in data maintenance and processing data analysis and the design of experiments of target domains which data will provide insight and knowledge traditional analysis in the area using puting and data services revolves around the creation of physicsbased models these are developed and executed by geoscience professionals with deep understanding of geology geophysics engineering reservoir dynamics production technology and economics among other things data managers support these geoscience professionals to ensure highquality data that powers the decisionmaking process in contexts with high data density significant actions are now being invested in advanced analytical techniques such machine learning to augment decisions traditionally made exclusively by geoscientists and engineers many scientists panies believe that they can generate fresh insight reduce decision cycle times and steal march on petition by automating the search patterns and relationships in their data therefore geophysics and data science including algorithms mathematical models puting must converge developing experiments obtaining insight and foresight about the observations contained in data collections furthermore experiments represent best practices addressing problems and questions on geophysics that must be treated data and knowledge to be shared and reused by scientists and practitioners topics of interest statistical methods to investigate unveil new geophysical data patterns answer open problems lead to further research questions unveil new geophysical data patterns answer open problems lead to new research questions parallelizing algorithms processing geophysical data in reasonable times lectures keynotes scalable machine learning machine learning automation geophysics dummies data science platforms how to set data science experiments at different scales experiments reproducibility the what where and when of the spacetime cubes data science current status and trends realtime detection nucleation of small earthquakes in stable south america exciting challenges get together trivia and working time with couches every day data science geophysics demo fest awards to the best challenges solutions presentations inclusion and diversity in writing tips designing presentations we also encourage women and munities to attend and actively participate in the challenges session summit thematic school abaixo repasso mensagem programa google voltado desenvolvimento pequenos projetos google summer of code gsoc will begin accepting student applications on march the global online program is designed to engage university students with open source munities gsoc is petitive and unique program in the past years we have had over students from countries accepted into the program participants are paired with mentor to help introduce them to an open munity and guide them with their project gsoc gives students invaluable real world experience and an opportunity to receive stipend to contribute to open source software the program open source organizations have been accepted into the program now is great time students to check out project ideas and reach out to the organizations to learn more we would appreciate your help to spread the word about google summer of code to university students check out the resources below website gcogsoc student application window march april flyers slide decks logos project topics include cloud operating systems machine learning graphics medicine programming languages robotics physics science security and many more sample twitter university students receive mentorship and stipend to work on open source software through google summer of code applications are open march april gcogsoc details of the program are available on the program site and be sure to check out the advice students quick tips and the student guide more details on the whole program please contact us at if you have any questions

prazer convidar seguinte workshop lolita group logic language information theory and applications workshop on generalized quantifiers ufrn dec auditório dimap ufrn agradecemos participação ampla divulgação participação atividade plementar bcc speaker josenaldo araújo silva júnior title on the definability of monadic quantifiers in extensions of classical firstorder logic with identity tools proving positive and negative claims abstract among the relevant expressivity issues concerning the classical firstorder logic with identity fol and other logics built thereupon one finds the definability of monadic quantifiers it is possible example to define in fol the quantifier exists there exists only one however the same does not hold the quantifier exists_even there exists an even number of in this talk the formal notion of definability of monadic quantifiers in extensions of fol will be introduced and two methods proving claims like the ones about exists and exists_even will be presented speaker joão daniel dantas title applications to monadic undefinability abstract in this talk we will present some results about the undefinability of some monadic quantifiers in given logic although there are many quantifiers that we use in natural language in sentences such each child is singing or most students will pass classical first order logic with identity historically favored the exclusive use of the quantifiers all and there is natural question that arises concerns which other quantifiers may be defined in fol with the help of the latter more traditional quantifiers in this talk we explore the formal tools that help one deciding when certain quantifier is not definable in logic focussing in method that allows proving the undefinability of monadic quantifier in given logic some examples of the quantifiers that we will explore include there are infinitely many there is an even number of and most are bs speaker thiago nascimento silva title an introduction to ehrenfeuchtfraissé games and their relation with definability of generalized quantifiers abstract in this talk we shall introduce range of games in model theory in each turn of these games while one player is trying to show that two structures are similar the other player is trying to show that they are different knowing which player has winning strategy that is knowing whether given player is able to win matter what her opponent does allows us to verify whether given logic allows the definability of certain quantifiers an interesting aspect of these games is that the methods that they provide are not restricted to monadic quantifiers link

discente joao helis junior azevedo bernardo data hora imdcivt auditorio b título the impact of adopting continuous integration on the delivery time of merged pull requests an empirical study resumo continuous integration ci is software development practice that leads developers to integrate their work more frequently software projects oadly adopted ci to ship new releases more frequently and to improve code integration the adoption of ci is usually motivated by the allure of delivering new software content more quickly and frequently however there is little empirical evidence to support such claims over the last years many available software projects from social coding environments such github have adopted the ci practice using ci facilities that are integrated into these environments eg travisci in this dissertation we empirically investigate the impact of adopting ci on the timetodelivery of pull requests prs through the analysis of prs of github projects that are implemented in different programming languages the results show that median of of merged pull requests have their delivery postponed by at least one release before adopting ci while after adopting ci median of of merged prs have their delivery postponed to future releases contrary to what one might speculate we find that prs tend to wait longer to be delivered after the adoption of ci in the majority of the studied projects the large increase of pr submissions after ci is key reason to why these projects deliver prs more slowly after adopting ci of the projects increase the rate of pr submissions after adopting ci to investigate the factors that are related to the timetodelivery of merged prs we train linear and logistic regression models which obtain sound median rsquares of and good median auc values of deeper analysis of our models suggests that before and after the adoption of ci the intensity of code contributions to release may increase the delivery time due to higher integrationload regarding mits of the development team finally we are able to accurately identify merged pull requests that have prolonged delivery time our regression models obtained median auc values of to palestra divulgação kaust datahorário auditório npiti visiting students research program kaust is an international graduatelevel research university located on the shores of the red sea in saudi arabia with student body representing over nations the university attracts worldclass faculty and top international scientists engineers and students to conduct fundamental and goaloriented research to address the worlds pressing scientific and technological problems the universitys new facilities and stateoftheart technology offer an ideal setting to study and conduct highimpact research currently the university has students with one of the most selective admission rates ing from saudi arabia china asia middle east europe americas and in the nature index rising stars kaust was ranked in the world of the fastest rising universities high quality research output kaust was also ranked the worlds top university in citations per faculty ranking indicator per qs world university rankings and in addition kaust was ranked in the percentage of international student and in the percentage of international faculty internship program the newly established visiting student research internship program is an opportunity exceptionally qualified baccalaureate and postbaccalaureate students to conduct research with faculty mentors in selected areas of basic and applied research projects the duration of the program ranges between three and six months depending on the research project kaust vsrp visiting students will receive the following academic credit monthly living allowance between based upon field of research roundtrip airfare tofrom city of departurejeddah kaust health insurance private bedroom bath in shared residential suite visa fees students must have valid passport access munity recreational resources social and cultural activities academic facilities advanced anes and porous materials catalysis center desert agriculture clean combustion computational bioscience geometric modeling and scientific visualization red sea solar and photovoltaics engineering and water desalination and reuse analytical chemistry biosciences and bioengineering coastal and marine resources imaging and characterization nano ication visualization core lab puting core lab and workshops palestra técnica widerange highlyefficient wireless power receivers biomedical sensors datahorário auditório npiti wireless power transfer wpt is the key enabler myriads of applications starting from lowpower rfids wireless sensors and internetofthings iot grow ing to wirelessly charged electric vehicles and even up to massive power transmission from space solar cells one of the major challenges to design tiny implantable biomed ical devices are the size and lifetime of the battery we propose miniaturized fullyintegrated wirelessly powered implantable sensor with onchip antennas designed and implemented in standard μm cmos process batteryless device it can be implanted once inside the body with need further invasive surgeries to replace batteries the proposed singlechip solution is designed and optimized intraocular pressure monitoring iopm and can serve sustainable sensing platform any implantable device or iot nodes we propose selfbiased crosscoupled differential rectifier with enhanced powerconversion efficiency over an extended range of input power prototype is designed uhf mhz rf powerharvesting applications and is implemented using ams μm cmos technology it demonstrates an efficiency improvement of more than in the rectifier power conversion efficiency pce and an input power range extension of more than relative to the conventional crosscoupled rectifier we further propose widerange differential rftodc power converter using an adaptive selfbiasing technique the proposed architecture extends the optimal input range at which the rectifier maintains of its peak power conversion efficiency over wider than conventional rectifiers unlike the continuously selfbiased rectifier proposed in the second part this adaptive selfbiased rectifier extends the dynamic range while maintaining both the high pce peak and the sensitivity advantage of the conventional crosscoupled scheme prof khaled nabil salama phd professor salamas research interests cover variety of interdisciplinary aspects of electronic circuit design and semiconductors ication he is engaged in developing devices circuits systems and algorithms to enable inexpensive analytical platforms variety of industrial environmental and biomedical applications recently he has been working on neuromorphic circuits ain emulation

dia auditório npiti hs dynamic programming based segmentation in biomedical imaging kathrin ungru research assistant at university of applied sciences münster department of electrical engineering and computer science many applications in biomedical imaging have demand on automatic detection of lines and boundaries of organs bones vessels and cells aim is to support expert decisions in interactive applications like contour tracking volume estimation etc or to include object segmentation part of fully automatic processing pipeline image analysis contour detection in biomedical images often suffers from noisy data and fuzzy edges around the objects of interest therefore there is need robust methods to perform contour detection and segmentation tasks dynamic programming is popular technique that satisfies these requirements in many ways it is an efficient method to find contours and lines in images based on discrete energy minimization dynamic programming always finds connected path with minimal energy even in the presence of holes in the objects boundary this talk gives ief overview of main methods that utilize dynamic programming to find single or multiple straight or circular contours in images dia auditório npiti hs what seems to be the trouble with energy and resources prof dr rer nat habil reinhart job dean muenster university of applied sciences department of electrical engineering and computer science the talk tries to answer two questions modern societies have real problem with the supply of energy can we provide the actual western style of living in sustainable way from the point of view of materials and materials research the speaker describes the development of modern technological societies the argumentation stresses that the development of societies correlates to the progress of science and especially to the progress of materials research with this regard the evolution of societies towards our modern highly engineered western style of living bases on steady supply with numerous materials and resources hence the speaker expects that limited resources in the future have strong impact on the further evolution of our societies albert einstein said we cant solve problems by using the same kind of thinking we used when we created them according to einsteins statement and concerning the technology and economy of the future some major changes seem to be necessary otherwise neither significant further progress on the long term can be expected the modern highly technologized western societies nor and this is painful closure of the gap between the rich countries and the developing world the argumentation of the speaker predicates on basic physical principles

lolita seminars ufrn may anfiteatro b ccet prazer confirmar seminário lolita group logic language information theory and applications agradecemos participação ampla divulgação speaker diana costa universidade aveiro title an overview on id logic abstract id logic is valuable tool specifying relational structures at the same time that it allows defining accessibility relations between states it provides way to name and mention what happens at each specific state in standard knowledge bases id knowledge bases ie sets of information specified by id formulas may contain inconsistencies coming from different sources namely from the very mechanisms used to collect the relevant information being fact rather than queer anomaly inconsistency also needs to be addressed in the context of id logic applications i will introduce paraconsistent version of id logic which is able to modate inconsistencies at points without implying global failure main feature of the resulting logic crucial to our approach is the fact that every id formula has an equivalent formula in negation normal form it will also be defined measure to quantify the inconsistency of id knowledge base useful possible basis paring knowledge bases the presentation will end with the introduction of prooftheoretical aspects namely it will be presented plete tableau system id logic bining both tableaux quasiclassical and id logics direct link calendar

divulgo novamente seminário prof achim jung afeira notem mudança tema ficou atraente acessível imperdível lolita seminars ufrn apr anfiteatro b ccet prazer confirmar seminário lolita group logic language information theory and applications agradecemos participação ampla divulgação speaker achim jung university of birmingham title the surprising difficulty of using mathematics puter science abstract in the noble prize winner eugene wigner gave talk with the title the unreasonable effectiveness of mathematics in the natural sciences writeup is easily available on the internet iefly wigner argued that in the natural sciences and in physics in particular mathematics exhibits an priori usefulness and he speculates why this should be so puter science we also use mathematical language and mathematical theories but one should perhaps not speak so much of applicability of one to the other but of rich and constantly evolving relationship between the two disciplines i will trace one instance of this relationship that which starts with churchs lambda calculus in the s and has since led to the development of programming languages such haskell direct link calendar

lolita seminars ufrn apr anfiteatro b ccet prazer confirmar próximos seminários lolita group logic language information theory and applications agradecemos participação ampla divulgação speaker umberto rivieccio ufrn title on extensions of the belnapdunn logic abstract belnapdunn logic is wellknown fourvalued logic that has been widely applied puter science since its introduction in the s from an aic logic point of view it is an interesting natural example of aic logic i will take look at extensions ie stronger logics but in the same language of this logic the aim would be to describe their hierarchy and providing axiomatizations some of them however major difficulties in plishing this stem from the fact that most extensions of belnapdunn are themselves aic and there are infinitely many of them direct link speaker achim jung university of birmingham title topological route towards fourvalued logic abstract i am planning this talk to have three parts i will begin by explaining the basic motivations and principles of denotational semantics and domain theory initiated by dana scott in particular i will stress the appearance of topology in this enterprise in the second part i will give an introduction to samson abramskys programme of domain theory in logical form which employs stone duality to link denotational semantics to program logic in the third part i will report on my own work with drew moshier and others on extending domain theory in logical form to pass more classical mathematical spaces such the real line we will see how form of fourvalued logic arises from this enterprise direct link calendar

lolita seminars ufrn mar anfiteatro ccet prazer confirmar seminário lolita group logic language information theory and applications agradecemos participação ampla divulgação speaker elaine pimentel dmat ufrn title proof search modal logics joint work with björn lellmann abstract main concern in proof theory modal logics is the development of philosophically and at the same putationally satisfying frameworks to capture large classes of logics in uniform and systematic way unfortunately the standard sequent framework satisfies these desiderata only partly undoubtedly there are sequent calculi number of modal logics exhibiting many good properties such analyticity which can be used plexityoptimal decision procedures however their construction often seems adhoc they are usually not modular and they mostly lack philosophically relevant properties such separate left and right introduction rules the modalities these problems are often connected to the fact that the modal rules in such calculi usually introduce more than one connective at time one way of solving this problem is to consider extensions of the sequent framework that are expressive enough capturing these modalities using separate left and right introduction rules this is possible eg in the frameworks of labelled sequents or in that of nested sequents or treehypersequents intuitively in the latter framework single sequent is replaced with tree of sequents where successors of sequent are interpreted under modality the modal rules of these calculi govern the transfer of modal formulae between the different sequents and it can be shown that it is sufficient to transfer only one formula at time however the price to pay this added expressivity is that the obvious proof search procedure is of plexity since it constructs potentially exponentially large nested sequents in this work we reconcile the added superior expressiveness and modularity of nested sequents with putational behaviour of the standard sequent framework by proposing focusing discipline linear nested sequents restricted form of nested sequents where the treestructure is restricted to that of line the result is notion of normal derivations in the linear nested setting which directly correspond to derivations in the standard sequent setting moreover the resulting labelled calculi lend themselves to specification and implementation in linear logic since we are interested in the connections to the standard sequent framework we concentrate on logics which have standard sequent calculus with examples including normal modal logic k and simple extensions family of simply dependent bimodal logics and also several nonnormal modal logics ie standard extensions of classical modal logic side effect we obtain to the best of our knowledge the first nested sequent calculi all the considered nonnormal modal logics direct link calendar

lolita seminars ufrn mar anfiteatro ccet prazer confirmar seminário lolita group logic language information theory and applications agradecemos participação ampla divulgação speaker carlos olarte ect ufrn title proof theoretic view of spatial and temporal dependencies in biochemical systems joint work with d chiarugi and m falaschi abstract the behaviour of biochemical systems such metabolic and signaling pathways may depend on either the location of the reactants or on the time needed reaction to occur in this talk we propose formalism specifying and verifying properties of biochemical systems bines coherently temporal and spatial modalities to this aim we consider fragment of intuitionistic linear logic with subexponentials sell the subexponential signature allows us to capture the spatial relations among the ponents of the system and the timed constraints we illustrate our approach by specifying some wellknown biological systems and verifying properties of them moreover we show that our framework is general enough to give logicbased semantics to psystems we show that the proposed logical characterizations has strong level of adequacy hence derivations in sell follow exactly the behavior of the modeled system direct link calendar

lolita seminars ufrn dec auditório b civt prazer convidar colegas seminário lolita group logic language information theory and applications haniel aluno graduação mestrado dimap ppgsc professor substituto primeiras turmas graduação imd encontra hoje doutoramento frança agradecemos participação ampla divulgação speaker haniel barbosa inria nancy veridis team at loria title satisfiability modulo theories handling quantifiers abstract in firstorder logic the _satisfiability modulo theories problem smt_ characterizes the search model given some formula which is consistent with set of background theories while in considering the ground case one usually deals with decidable fragment eg ground fol modulo presburger arithmetic when handling quantified formulas it is often necessary to work on undecidable or even plete settings since quantifiers are unavoidable in many problems like in formal verification of systems it is necessary to develop reasonably efficient algorithms even if nonterminating such problems in this talk we will focus on the automation of smt solving presenting the mon approaches their theory and organization in stateoftheart solver in particular the techniques developed to handle quantified problems will be shown in detail direct link calendar

lolita seminars ufrn oct prazer convidar seguintes seminários lolitaufrn group logic language information theory and applications the temporal logic week ufrn imd horário tuesday temporal logic an introduction auditório b lecturers sidemar fideles cezario thiago soares marques abstract this presentation will be an introduction to temporal logic first we will introduce terminology used in temporal logic well its standard semantics and axioms we will also discuss the applications of temporal logic in computer science wednesday model checking with temporal logic general motivation auditório b lecturer karydja redyjane medeiros souza abstract temporal logic has applications in model checking in helping to demonstrate that system is correct that means its specifications are met this presentation will talk about the use of model checking in the particular case of the concurrent systems we will introduce the formal definition of concurrent program followed by petersons algorithm which allows two processes to share mon resource with conflict finally we will see that programs correctness can be verified even when this program takes the form of an automaton thursday verification via linear temporal logic applications auditório b lecturers hiago mayk gomes araujo rocha lucas simonetti marinho cardoso abstract this presentation will be about linear temporal logic ltl we will introduce ltl and explain how it can be defined by extending the classical propositional logic with temporal operations its semantics properties and what are the structures used to interpret the formulas the concept of ωlanguages will also be introduced paying special attention to ωregular languages which is the type of languages used to create an interpretation the propositions of temporal logic about büchi automata and about the concepts of safety liveness and fairness friday verification via computation tree logic applications auditório b lecturers luis tertulino cunha neto ronaldo figueiredo silveira abstract computation tree logic ctl just linear time logic ltl is an area of temporal logic that introduces ways of thinking about paths in the future that can be taken or not the statement its possible that from some point on it will be cold in natal can only be logically represented with the ideas of more than one possibilities of future these notions are well represented using ctl this presentation will introduce ctl and its applications puter science mainly to model checking princípio palestras oferecidas português direct link calendar agradecemos evento lolita group logic language information theory and applications dimapufrn palestras lógica putação quântica oferecidas visitantes itália inglaterra agradecemos participação ampla divulgação nota participação evento contabilizada atividade seminários cc speakers alessandra di pierro univr it title calculus topological quantum computation luca viganò kings college london uk title modal and temporal deduction systems quantum state transformations abstract calculus topological quantum computation recent developments in theoretical physics have highlighted interesting topological features of some particular twodimensional entities called anyons the idea of using these features to realise robust putation has introduced the study of the new paradigm of topological quantum computation tqc the mathematics and physics of anyons is currently subject to intense investigations in all areas related to the study of putation from both the foundational and the implementation viewpoint in this talk we take puter science viewpoint of tqc by presenting formal calculus whose syntax and reduction relation are able to capture the putational mechanism of the anyons manipulation in tqc abstract modal and temporal deduction systems quantum state transformations modal and temporal logics have proven suitable to formally represent and reason about transformations of quantum states in an abstract qualitative way quantum states represent quantum systems and can be viewed the structure of quantum data quantum operations in this talk i will first introduce modal framework reasoning about operations on quantum states unitary transformations and measurements in terms of possible worlds abstractions of quantum states and accessibility relations between these worlds then i will present the distributed temporal logic dtl which allows one to reason about temporal properties of distributed system from the point of view of the systems agents which are assumed to execute independently and to interact by means of event sharing i will introduce the quantum distributed branching temporal logic qdtl variant of dtl able to represent quantum state transformations in more satisfactory way than simple modal systems in qdtl each agent represents distinct quantum bit the unit of quantum information theory which evolves by means of quantum transformations and possibly interacts with other agents nary quantum operators act municationsynchronization points between agents qdtl is endowed with dtlstyle semantics which fits the intrinsically distributed nature of puting finally i will discuss possible extensions in order to reason about entanglement phenomena joint work with andrea masini marco volpe margherita zorzi direct link calendar
